WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:04.000
This is kind of fun. This is a new thing in Vitest.

00:04.000 --> 00:09.000
So copy this one with me. Come in here and you can stop this.

00:09.000 --> 00:18.000
We're going to say npm install capital D at Vitest

00:18.000 --> 00:26.000
slash UI at 2.1.3.

00:26.000 --> 00:30.000
And in our scripts here, we're just going to add another one here.

00:30.000 --> 00:36.000
It's going to be test colon UI.

00:36.000 --> 00:43.000
And it's going to be Vitest dash dash UI.

00:43.000 --> 00:46.000
There's nothing special about this colon. That's just the way that I like structuring my commands.

00:46.000 --> 00:50.000
This is a test, but we want the UI version of it.

00:50.000 --> 00:53.000
You could also call this test colon coverage. That's actually probably what I would call it.

00:53.000 --> 00:58.000
But everyone else calls like coverage, so I just stick to the convention.

00:58.000 --> 01:05.000
But we have test UI here. Let's go try that. npm run test colon UI.

01:05.000 --> 01:10.000
And you get this kind of like nice in browser experience with Vitest.

01:10.000 --> 01:15.000
So you can see it ran my tests. They all passed the amount of time it took.

01:15.000 --> 01:22.000
You can only look at the failing ones. You can run them individually if you want to.

01:22.000 --> 01:26.000
You can't run the snapshot one because it's a snapshot test.

01:26.000 --> 01:33.000
But all that stuff works. There's a module graph. You can see what it depends on, which is kind of cool.

01:33.000 --> 01:37.000
They move around. This is extremely useful. You can see the code behind them.

01:37.000 --> 01:43.000
You can see what they log out to the console. You don't have anything in there, so it won't do that.

01:43.000 --> 01:47.000
But yeah, it's kind of cool, right? That's it. That's the whole thing.

01:47.000 --> 01:52.000
This is neat. I should show people this, right? That's the whole story.

01:52.000 --> 01:56.000
You know what? I haven't shown you so far. Let's just go ahead and do it now.

01:56.000 --> 02:01.000
We haven't downloaded the VS Code extension for Vitest, and it's very cool.

02:01.000 --> 02:09.000
So come to VS Code. Come in here and do Vitest. I have it down here.

02:09.000 --> 02:14.000
So make sure you're getting Vitest from Vitest. And install that.

02:14.000 --> 02:18.000
I'm going to shut this down for a second so I can show you this.

02:18.000 --> 02:22.000
Once you have that, you'll have this testing thing here on the side.

02:22.000 --> 02:26.000
For whatever reason, mine wasn't showing up. So if you had the same problem as me,

02:26.000 --> 02:30.000
like it wasn't showing up with the Vitest thing and saying, like, you need to install Python stuff or something like that,

02:30.000 --> 02:36.000
just navigate to it, disable it, uninstall it, and then reinstall it. That should work.

02:36.000 --> 02:42.000
You can also always say Shift-Command-P or Control-Shift-P and reload window here.

02:42.000 --> 02:46.000
That usually fixes almost all my VS Code problems.

02:46.000 --> 02:53.000
All right. So now I have here my source directory and my test directory. I can see all of my tests.

02:53.000 --> 02:58.000
You can actually see, you can go and see the individual tests in here as well.

02:58.000 --> 03:04.000
And let's just go ahead and run everything, right? Let's just get crazy.

03:04.000 --> 03:08.000
I'll give you all the test coverage stuff in here so you can see all the various things that it is covering.

03:08.000 --> 03:13.000
You can run tests individually. Pretty cool to come in here.

03:13.000 --> 03:20.000
And let's use this one and just say, I don't know, not to be null or something like that.

03:20.000 --> 03:24.000
Something that's definitely going to fail. Notice there's a check mark here.

03:24.000 --> 03:32.000
I'm going to save this. And if I click to run this, it's actually going to run that test individually.

03:32.000 --> 03:37.000
And it's going to tell me it broke on this line for this reason.

03:37.000 --> 03:42.000
Pretty cool to see that directly in your browsers. Like this is the thing that broke.

03:42.000 --> 03:47.000
I think it's pretty compelling. So a lot of times I won't even run the command line client.

03:47.000 --> 03:52.000
I'll just rely on this to do it itself.

03:52.000 --> 03:55.000
And now I can run this again and it'll turn up just fine.

03:55.000 --> 04:00.000
And then you can do the start continuous run.

04:00.000 --> 04:07.000
Let's do it this way. Run. OK. Or I guess we can do the coverage. That's fine.

04:07.000 --> 04:16.000
And so now I'm not even going to press the button. I'm just going to say not and save it.

04:16.000 --> 04:18.000
And it's going to just immediately run it in the background.

04:18.000 --> 04:21.000
Every time I save the file, it's going to keep running and rerunning my tests, which is kind of cool.

04:21.000 --> 04:28.000
And it's actually smart to say, like, this test only tests this file. It'll only run those specific ones, which is pretty cool.

04:28.000 --> 04:33.000
It's kind of like there's many ways to go about doing this. So just pick your favorite.

04:33.000 --> 04:39.000
If you like the CLI, by all means stick with that. If you like the UI version, you can do everything through the UI.

04:39.000 --> 04:44.000
I'm in VS Code all day, so I tend to use VS Code or the CLI, but that's totally up to you.

